│ length yields poison. In the source, %ins = insertelement <2 x i8> poison,  │
│ i8 %x, i32 3 results in a poison vector because index 3 is out of bounds.   │
│ The vector division with a constant vector <5,2> then yields poison (since  │
│ poison op anything = poison). The transformation incorrectly extracts       │
│ element at index 3 from the constant vector VecC1 (<5,2>) via               │
│ ConstantExpr::getExtractElement, which is undefined behavior because index  │
│ 3 is out of bounds for a 2-element vector. This results in poison being     │
│ used as the second operand to the scalar division, making the scalar        │
│ division have a poison divisor, which triggers undefined behavior (UB) when │
│ %x is poison (as shown in the counterexample). The source had no UB (just   │
│ poison results), but the target introduces UB.                              │
│                                                                             │
│ 2. Analyzing `opt`'s Log: The debug log shows that IsConst1 is true (V1 is  │
│ null), Index0=3, Index1=0, Index=IsConst0?Index1:Index0 = Index0 = 3. At    │
